article.headline: Kidd adds 54th triple-double
article.story:
EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- With the New Jersey Nets riding a four-game losing streak and the pressure mounting, Byron Scott asked his team and his stars for a little more on Friday night. Kenyon Martin, Jason Kidd, Kerry Kittles and Richard Jefferson stepped up for their embattled coach. Martin had 20 points and matched his career-high with 21 rebounds and Kidd recorded his 54th career triple-double in leading the struggling Nets to a 93-86 win over the Milwaukee Bucks. "Our guys are going to follow those two guys," Scott said of Kidd and Martin. "When Jason comes out and plays like he played, and Kenyon plays with that type of emotion, our team feeds off that. That's what we have been missing. "I challenged those guys before the game, and this is the way we have to play," Scott added. "Like I said after the game, this is a start, we have to continue to try to get better." Playing before a crowd of about 3,000 due to a snowstorm, Kidd finished with 16 points, 11 assists and 10 rebounds to help the two-time defending Eastern Conference champions (8-11) take a little pressure off Scott, who is in the final year of his contract. Kittles added 22 points and Jefferson had 18 for New Jersey, which won for only the third time in nine home games. "After the last game, I had a long thinking session with myself," said Martin, who had five big-time dunks. "I know what I need to do to play the way I am capable of playing. I had a talk with Byron and I gave my word that I would play the way I am capable of playing." Michael Redd had 24 points and Desmond Mason added 19 for the Bucks, who played without Toni Kukoc (back spasms) and Tim Thomas (ankle). Martin, who had 13 defensive rebounds, had four of his dunks in a 22-10 spurt that gave New Jersey a six-point halftime lead. The Nets appeared to break the game open with a 13-2 spurt that gave them a 59-42 lead early in the third quarter. "We let them get a little momentum in the second quarter and they kept it for the rest of the game," Redd said. "It was just too deep a hole to come back from. The Bucks nearly did. Redd pulled them to 90-84 on a jumper with 1:16 to go, but Kidd put the game away with a 3-pointer with 19 seconds to play. "It was going out there and playing the way you are capable of playing, in a sense of showcasing your talent and not being Beverly Hills," Kidd said. "We came out of the game like the old Nets, in the sense of being aggressive, playing up-tempo, getting stops, getting out and running and just having fun." The triple-double was Kidd's fourth of the season. No other NBA player has more than one triple-double this season.

Game notes
The crowd was announced as 14,154. ... The Bucks placed Kukoc (back spasms) on the injured list before the game. F Dan Langhi was signed but he won't join the team until Saturday night in Milwaukee against Washington. ... Thomas missed his fifth straight game with a sprained ankle. ... New Jersey outrebounded Milwaukee 50-39. ... The Bucks had more fast-break points than the Nets, 13-12.
